ce:section.ce:para:
Accumulation time and potential is an important parameters for enhancing the sensitivity of the imprinted sensor [22]. Hence, Influences of the accumulation time and the accumulation potential were investigated in buffer solution containing 100 μM SOT by the CV method. The accumulation time was changed from 10 s to 100 s. The results showed peak current enhanced meaningfully by the increase of the accumulation time to 100 s, and after the 70 s peak current reduced so, 70 s was used in the subsequent experiments (Fig. 8
                        ). Similarly, the dependence of the accumulation potential on the peak current of 50 μM SOT from −0.8 to 0.5 V was examined. The cyclic voltammograms in Fig. 9
                         corroborated that the extreme peak current took place at -0.6 V. Hence, for further study the accumulation potential of -0.6 V was chosen.

In order to assess that the presented sensor was selective to detect SOT, under the optimum conditions the sensor response was examined by various potentially interference species. Interferences from similar compound such as captopril, glucose, cystamine, urea, alanine, ripaglinide, terazosin, valproate and cysteine on the surface of the sensor at the amount of 100 μM for apiece interference in the attendance of 5 μM of SOT were used as indicators for the selectivity of the sensor in comparison with the estimate of SOT alone (Table 2
                         and Fig. 11
                        ). The results suggested that the proposed MIP-sensor strategy had high specificity for SOT detection.
